post_text:
Windsor Public Schools plans to re-open schools on Tuesday, September 8 on a hybrid model. To learn more about this model, please review the Reopening Plan found on the District Website under Reopening https://www.windsorct.org/wps-reopening-plan-2020-21.
If, after reviewing the plan, you wish to opt your child out of in-person learning, please complete the Opt-out form also found on the website by no later than Tuesday, August 18 at 11:59PM so that schools have time to plan for the first day of school.
text:
Windsor Public Schools plans to re-open schools on Tuesday, September 8 on a hybrid model. To learn more about this model, please review the Reopening Plan found on the District Website under Reopening https://www.windsorct.org/wps-reopening-plan-2020-21.
If, after reviewing the plan, you wish to opt your child out of in-person learning, please complete the Opt-out form also found on the website by no later than Tuesday, August 18 at 11:59PM so that schools have time to plan for the first day of school.

post_text:
With all of the reopening communications being pushed out to families, it is important to check if you received the most recent communication via phone, email or text from the district on Thursday, August 13 regarding Reopening.

If you did not receive that message, please check your email to make sure that you have completed the annual PowerSchool Update. As of Wednesday, August 12, families who have not yet updated their contact information in PowerSchool will no longer receive communications from the school district.

If you are not receiving school or district communications via phone, email, or text, and you are unable to locate the email to update your PowerSchool contact information, please click the link below to inform your child’s school. https://forms.gle/eaBTrtCNtPum1x1t8

Please see updates to Grab-N-Go Meal schedule. #WPSDistanceLearning
No Grab & Go Food Service at Clover Street School.
Grab & Go Food Service will be available at Windsor High School and Oliver Ellsworth, Wednesday April 8 & Thursday April 9.
NO Grab & Go Food Service on Good Friday April 10; however, extra food will be put in bags on Thursday, April 9.
Families will only get one bag per student.
During Vacation week, April 13-April 17, we will have Grab & Go Food Service only at Windsor High School.

post_text:
Don't miss this! WPS Neighborhood Distance Learning Parade will take place beginning at 12:20 PM Tuesday, March 31. Teachers and staff will parade through neighborhood streets in their cars honking car horns to wave hello to you. For the safety of all, please be mindful to practice social distancing and do not stand in the streets. View links below to find parade routes and a flyer about the Distance Learning Parade. #WPSDistanceLearning

post_text: Carrie Sawtel, holding an anatomical acupuncture model, is the owner and acupuncturist of Many Rivers Acupuncture. She recently spoke to Mr. Chrisis's Introduction to Health Care classes about the growing field of acupuncture and the healing benefits of acupuncture as an alternative or complement to allopathic treatments most people seek out from their family doctor. The ancient Chinese healing practice of acupuncture is even used before and after surgeries within hospitals such as St. Francis Hospital in nearby Hartford. The Intro to Health Care students have learned about the high costs of healthcare in previous lessons. They were quite happy to learn that Many Rivers Acupuncture is a community acupuncture treatment center located in Bloomfield and has a very reasonable sliding scale payment system which allows for many people to be able to access this treatment.

post_text: 53 students from Mr. Chrisis’ Intro to Health Care classes learned about emergency medicine, preventing car crashes and how to stop a person from bleeding out from a severe injury. Denecia Hastings and Emily Anderson portrayed emergency room health care providers while Claudier Albert portrayed an accident victim. Later in the day the students learned the facts about organ donation and then were trained and certified for completing the Bleeding Control Basic course from the American College of Surgeons. Each student was then presented with a personalized certificate. A special thank you to science teacher Michelle Desroschers, two science interns along with two parents and another Windsor High School alumna who served as chaperones for a successful day.

post_text: On September 11, Mary Mackey and Esther Cochran of the Alzheimer’s Association along with Kate Bartelmo a Director from Kimberly Hall visited Mr. Chrisis’s UCONN Human Development and Family Studies (HDFS) Early College Experience class in order to raise awareness about the disease and also to recruit students to serve as volunteers at the next Walk to End Alzheimer’s. The students will meet with other volunteers from the general area in Enfield on September 22, 2019 for the event. The students were also offered other leadership opportunities available throughout the year in order to help raise awareness to stem the disease. The HDFS students must complete 40 internship hours in order to earn UCONN credit along with earning a passing academic grade.

post_text: The Gene Haas Foundation Scholarship is provided due to the generosity of Gene Haas, the owner and founder of Haas Automation, Inc., America’s leading builder of CNC machine tools. Gene’s commitment to the importance of US manufacturing has incited him to grow his personal foundation and direct his foundation board to focus on manufacturing education and providing scholarship grants for students entering CNC machinist training or a field utilizing this technology. The one time non-renewable $3,000 award will go to two highly qualified applicants and must be paid directly to the business office of the appropriate college or university.

post_text:
Current HS Juniors, apply to SWEAT this July. http://bit.ly/whssweat

To learn more, please watch this 2-minute student video that describes the SWEAT experience: https://youtu.be/XS3RZfJhJlA

The SWEAT program (Senior Workshops Enabling a Smooth Academic Transition) is series of workshops focused on helping incoming seniors take a weight off their shoulders and get their post-secondary materials completed or started prior to entering into senior year. The three workshops offered to students are The College Application Process, The College Essay, and Resume Writing and Letters of Recommendation. Each workshop also involves SAT prep to help students boost their scores, as well as a crash course in college jargon to help students become aware of the financial aid, admissions, and academic language of the college world. Attendance for each day of the workshop you are enrolled in is mandatory.

Each workshop will also award one student a scholarship of $250 based on consistent attendance, participation, merit, and need.

To apply for the program, http://bit.ly/whssweat

Want to improve education in Windsor Public Schools?

Share this post and your thoughts on our Thoughtexchange site. https://my.thoughtexchange.com/#175774023

Here is our topic: What are the most important skills and attributes Windsor students need to develop in order to ensure success in learning, life, and work beyond school?

So far, we've had 548 thoughts shared from 506 participants (79% students, 15% parents, 1% community)

The image attached to this post shows the current top 3 thoughts. Do you agree?

If you've already been into Thoughtexchange, please return and add ⭐️ to the new thoughts that have been added since you participated. Your ⭐️ will help us understand what's most important to our stakeholders. We really want to hear from you.

Fun fact about Windsor Food Service:

Did you know that Sage Park and Windsor High cafeterias are growing their own organic greens?

For the past five weeks, using EvanLEE Organics grow racks, the cafeterias have been growing organic microgreens, basil, lemon basil, parsley, cilantro, and crispino (a cross between green leaf and head lettuce).

Students find these healthy greens in their lunchtime salads and sauces. Fresh basil is added to their pizza, and fresh cilantro is added to the bean salsa.

In the photos, WHS cafeteria manager, Cindy Todd, shows what's growing!

Good news from Ms. Lloyd, elementary art teacher:

As of this week, there is a regional display of student art at Bradley International Airport in the hallway in between the Sheraton and the airport terminals. The display features work by students from Windsor, Windsor Locks, Suffield, and East Granby. Windsor's display contains select art from all four elementary schools. Laila Ly was selected to represent JFK with her beautiful work on her mandala project. If you're traveling over April break I definitely recommend checking out the students' wonderful work!

The display is accessible through the hotel or through the airport. If you're going via the hotel, just walk straight in through the front door then turn left in the hallway with the windows. If you're going in through the airport, go to the west end (the end nearest the United Airlines’ ticket counter) and continue down the corridor. The displays are just past the Sheraton on the left side.

This weekend, set an alarm or your DVR so you don't miss Windsor High sparring against Suffield High on "As Schools Match Wits" airing on WGBY public television Saturday, March 30 at 7 p.m. (rebroadcast Sunday, March 31 at 10:30 a.m. and available for subsequent online streaming at video.wgby.org/show/as-schools-match-wits).

As Schools Match Wits (ASMW) pits teams of western New England high schoolers against each other in a fun, but competitive game of academic performance. The competition is open to both public and private high schools throughout western New England.

Each season, up to 50 schools go head-to-head in qualifying matches to see which team can earn the greatest number of points. The eight highest-scoring teams of the season then compete in playoff matches to determine the season’s champion, which is then awarded the coveted Collamore Cup, named for the show’s creator.

Go Warriors!

Know someone age 16 or older who seeks a driver's license? There's still space in Windsor Adult and Continuing Education's Complete Driver Education Course (DE002).

Convenient driver education classes taught by State of Connecticut licensed instructors at Windsor High! Includes 30 hours of classroom instruction and at least 8 hours of private, behind-the-wheel driving lessons. Driving lessons are one-on-one and begin and end at the WHS parking lot. Vehicles are all fully insured, with dual-control and maintained every 5,000 miles.

This course fulfills all state requirements for NEW drivers. Upon successful completion, students can test in 4 months.

Choose from the first or second 30-hour / 15-class session. Register at https://www.thenextstreet.com/ct-driving-schools/hartford-county/windsor-high-school or 860-631-4292.

Sessions: 15
Dates: 3/25/2019 to 5/20/2019
Meeting Times: Monday 2:45 PM - 4:45 PM and Wednesday 2:45 PM - 4:45 PM
Location: Windsor High School Rm. E101
Instructor: Staff Next Street
Fees: $529.00 (Class Fee)

Windsor Public Schools is accepting applications beginning on Monday, March 4, 2019 for the 2019-2020 preschool program. Children who will be three or four on or before January 1, 2020 are eligible to apply for preschool.

Half day and full day preschool classes are located at Oliver Ellsworth and Poquonock Schools in Windsor, Connecticut. Families must provide transportation for their students to and from school.

Preschool applications will be accepted on an ongoing basis throughout the year. The selection process for 2019-2020 openings will begin in April and families will be notified by May 10 regarding the status of their applications.
